[[File:Map of dialects of Lithuanian language.png|thumb|Map of the dialects of the Lithuanian language (Zinkevičius and Girdenis, 1965) {{legend|#aa51e7|Southern Aukštaitian or Dzūkian sub-dialect}}]]
'''Dzūkian dialect''', known in academic works as '''Southern Aukštaitian dialect''', is one of the three main sub-dialects of the [[Aukštaitian dialect]] of [[Lithuanian language]]. Dzūkian dialect is spoken in [[Dzūkija]], southern [[Lithuania]]. Its most distinctive feature is replacing ''t'', ''d'' before ''i'', ''į'', ''y'', ''ie'' and ''č'', ''dž'' with ''c'' and ''dz'' (''cik'' instead of ''tik'' – just, ''dzidumas'' instead of ''didumas'' – size, ''pync'' instead of ''pinti'' – to braid, ''sveciai'' instead of ''svečiai'' – guests). Since the region borders [[Slavs|Slavic]] lands, the dialect has many Slavic [[loanword]]s and [[barbarism (linguistics)|barbarism]]s.

