'''''Hungrvaka''''' ("Hunger-waker") is an [[Old Norse]] history of the first five [[Diocese of Skálholt|bishops of Skálholt]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=d-XiZO8V4qUC&lpg=PA307&ots=bvP6so6YSw&dq=hungrvaka%20medieval%20scandinavia&pg=PA307#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Medieval Scandinavia: An encyclopedia|last=Bibire|first=Paul|publisher=Garland|year=1993|isbn=0824047877|editor-last=Pulsiano|editor-first=Phillip|location=New York|pages=307|chapter=Hungrvaka|author-link=Paul Bibire|editor-last2=Bibire|editor-first2=Paul}}</ref> The text covers the period from the [[Christianization of Iceland|formation of the Icelandic church]] to 1178.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|title=Hungrvaka|last=Basset|first=Camilla|publisher=Háskóli Íslands (MA thesis)|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=1|archive-url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2016}}</ref> As the text refers to [[Saint Thorlak]] (acknowledged 1198), [[Jón Ögmundsson]] (acknowledged as a local Icelandic saint in 1200), and Gizzur Hallsson (died 1206), it was probably written in the first half of the thirteenth century.<ref name=":1" /> However, the manuscripts witnesses of the saga are all post-medieval, the earliest dating from 1601.<ref name=":0" /> Because of similarities in style it is assumed that the author of ''Hungrvaka'' wrote ''[[Páls saga biskups]]'' and may also have written passages of ''[[Þorláks saga helga]].''

The reason for the book's title is given by the author in the introduction:<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|title=Hungrvaka|last=Basset|first=Camilla|publisher=Háskóli Íslands (MA thesis)|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=3|archive-url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2016}}</ref>{{Quote|text=‘Bœkling þenna kalla ek Hungrvǫku, af því at svá mun mǫrgum mǫnnum ófróðum ok þó óvitrum gefit vera, þeim er hann hafa yfir farit, at miklu myndu gørr vilja vita upprás ok ævi þeira merkismanna er hér verðr fátt frá sagt á þessi skrá.’

‘I call this little book Hungrvaka because many men, unlearned and unwise as well, will be so disposed towards that which it has checked that they would wish to know more fully of the origin and lifetime of those remarkable men who shall briefly be recounted here in this written work.’|sign=|source=}}

== Bibliography ==

=== Manuscripts ===
A comprehensive treatment of the manuscripts can be found in Ásdís Egilsdóttir's introduction to ''Hungrvaka'' in the most recent edition of the text,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Biskupa sögur|last=Ásdís Egilsdóttir|first=|publisher=Hið íslenzka fornritafélag|year=2002|isbn=|editor-last=Ásdís Egilsdóttir|series=Íslenzk fornrit XVI|volume=Volume 2|location=Reykjavík|pages=vi-xxxi|chapter=Formáli, Hungrvaka}}</ref> and summarised by Basset.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|title=Hungrvaka|last=Basset|first=Camilla|publisher=Háskóli Íslands (MA thesis)|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=1–2|archive-url=http://skemman.is/stream/get/1946/15914/37945/1/CamillaCB_Hungrvaka_2013.pdf|archive-date=9 April 2016}}</ref>

The main manuscripts represent three versions of the text:<ref name=":1" />
* AM 380 4to, AM 379 4to (B)
* AM 205 fol., AM 375 4to, AM 378 4to (C)
* AM 110 8vo (D)

