{{Orphan|date=September 2014}}
{{Infobox building | building_name = Palazzo Dall’Armi Marescalchi | image = | caption = | image_size = 200px | location = [[Bologna]], Italy | geo = | location_town =Bologna | architect = | architecture_style = | groundbreaking_date = 1466 | year_completed = }} The '''Palazzo Dall’Armi Marescalchi''' is a [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] style palace in central [[Bologna]].
The palace was initially constructed in 1466, and rebuilt in 1613 by [[Floriano Ambrosini]]. The Marescalchi name was added when Eleonora D’Armi married Senator Vincenzo Marescalchi.
In the 1700s, further lands and gardens added. In the 19th century further reconstruction was pursued. The scientist [[Guglielmo Marconi]] was born in the palace. In 1961 it was acquired by the Ministry of the Treasury, and converted to house the ''Soprintendenza per i Beni Ambientali e Architettonici'' of the Province of Emilia. Some of the rooms on the main floor retain frescoes by [[Ludovico Carracci]] and [[Guido Reni]]. The large oval hall was frescoed by [[Felice Giani]] in 1780.<ref>[http://www.arte.it/guida-arte/bologna/da-vedere/monumento/palazzo-dall-armi-marescalchi-2251 Arte.it] website on palace.</ref> The palace suffered during the bombardments of World War II.<ref>[http://memoriadibologna.comune.bologna.it/palazzo-dallarmi-marescalchi-1323-luogo Memoria di Bologna] entry on palace, by Silvia Benati.</ref>
