[[File:Fortress of Guaita 2013-09-19.jpg|thumb|Guaita]] [[File:San Marino La Cesta o Fratta.jpg|thumb|Cesta]]
The '''Three Towers of San Marino''' are a group of towers located in [[San Marino]]. Located on the three peaks of [[Monte Titano]] in the capital, also called [[San Marino, San Marino|San Marino]], they are depicted on both the [[Flag of San Marino|national flag]] and [[Coat of Arms of San Marino|coat of arms]].
== First Tower == The '''[[Guaita]]''' is the oldest of the three towers, and the most famous. It was constructed in the 11th century and served briefly as a prison. It was rebuilt numerous times and reached its current form in the 15th century during the war fought between San Marino and the [[House of Malatesta]].<ref>{{cite web|title=First Tower (Guaita)|url=http://www.visitsanmarino.com/on-line/en/home/experience/arts-and-culture/scheda31097700.html|website=www.visitsanmarino.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>
== Second Tower == The '''[[Cesta]]''' is located on the highest of Monte Titano's summits. A museum to honour [[Saint Marinus]], created in 1956, is located in this tower and showcases over 1,550 weapons dating from the Medieval Era to the modern day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Museum of Historical Weapons|url=http://www.zainoo.com/en/italy/emilia-romagna/san-marino/museum-of-historical-weapons|website=www.zainoo.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref> It was constructed in the 13th century on the remains of an older Roman fort.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second Tower (Cesta)|url=http://www.visitsanmarino.com/on-line/en/home/experience/arts-and-culture/scheda31097701.html|website=www.visitsanmarino.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>
== Third Tower == [[File:Montale.JPG|thumb|Montale]] The '''[[Montale (San Marino)|Montale]]''' is located on the smallest of Monte Titano's summits. Unlike the other towers, this one is not open to the public. It was constructed in the 14th century. It is thought to have been constructed to give protection against the increasing power of the [[House of Malatesta|Malatesta]] family in that region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montale (Third Tower)|url=http://www.zainoo.com/en/italy/emilia-romagna/san-marino/montale|website=www.zainoo.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref> It was also used as a prison, and accordingly, the only entrance to the tower is a door about seven metres from ground level, which was common for prison architecture of the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Terza Torre (Montale)|url=http://www.visitsanmarino.com/on-line/en/home/experience/arts-and-culture/scheda31097705.html|website=www.visitsanmarino.com|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref>
